The paper deals with the problem of triangulating a simple polygon, which is a classic problem in computational geometry. Therefore, cs.CG (Computational Geometry) is the most likely sub-category. The algorithm presented in the paper is a time-space trade-off algorithm, which means it uses a limited amount of space to achieve a faster running time. This makes cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) likely sub-categories as well. The paper also uses randomized techniques, which suggests cs.CC (Computational Complexity) as a possible sub-category. Finally, the paper deals with the problem of triangulating a polygon, which is a problem in computational topology, making cs.DC (Discrete Geometry and Topology) a possible sub-category as well.
